====================================================================
JENKINS UPGRADE & BACKUP 
====================================================================

--------------------------------------------------
WHY DO WE UPGRADE JENKINS?
--------------------------------------------------

    • Security patches (very important)
    • Bug fixes
    • New features
    • Plugin compatibility
    • Performance improvements

    Regular upgrade is mandatory in production.


--------------------------------------------------
WHAT IS jenkins.war?
--------------------------------------------------

    jenkins.war is the core Jenkins application file.

    Location (Linux):

        /usr/share/java/jenkins.war

    Jenkins service runs using this WAR file.


--------------------------------------------------
IMPORTANT BEFORE UPGRADE
--------------------------------------------------

    ALWAYS take backup before upgrading.

    Backup includes:

        • jenkins.war file
        • Jenkins home directory


--------------------------------------------------
STEP 1: BACKUP jenkins.war and delete the war 
--------------------------------------------------

    systemctl stop jenkins 

    sudo cp -rp /usr/share/java/jenkins.war /usr/share/java/jenkins.war.bak_14apr2026
    cd /usr/share/java/
    rm -rf jenkins.war
    
--------------------------------------------------
STEP 2: BACKUP JENKINS HOME
--------------------------------------------------

    Jenkins home contains:

        • Jobs
        • Configurations
        • Plugins
        • Credentials

Location:

    /var/lib/jenkins/

Command:

    sudo cp -r /var/lib/jenkins \
        /var/lib/jenkins_backup


--------------------------------------------------
STEP 3: DOWNLOAD NEW JENKINS WAR
--------------------------------------------------

Command:
   
    cd /usr/share/java/

    sudo wget https://get.jenkins.io/war/2.559/jenkins.war


--------------------------------------------------
STEP 5: RESTART JENKINS
--------------------------------------------------

Command:

    sudo systemctl restart jenkins

    Check status:

        sudo systemctl status jenkins


--------------------------------------------------
STEP 6: VERIFY UPGRADE
--------------------------------------------------

    • Login to Jenkins UI
    • Check version in dashboard
    • Verify jobs are working


--------------------------------------------------
ROLLBACK (IF ISSUE OCCURS)
--------------------------------------------------

    Stop Jenkins:

        sudo systemctl stop jenkins

    Restore old WAR:

        sudo mv /usr/share/java/jenkins.war.bak_14apr2026 \
            /usr/share/java/jenkins.war

    Start Jenkins:

        sudo systemctl start jenkins


--------------------------------------------------
REAL DEVOPS BEST PRACTICE
--------------------------------------------------

    • Always test upgrade in staging first
    • Backup before upgrade
    • Check plugin compatibility
    • Upgrade plugins after Jenkins upgrade
    • Monitor logs after upgrade


--------------------------------------------------
IMPORTANT FILE LOCATIONS
--------------------------------------------------

    Jenkins WAR:
        /usr/share/java/jenkins.war

    Jenkins Home:
        /var/lib/jenkins/

    Logs:
        /var/log/jenkins/jenkins.log

=========================================================================================================================
JENKINS DISTRIBUTED ARCHITECTURE (MASTER–AGENT)
====================================================================

--------------------------------------------------
WHAT IS DISTRIBUTED ARCHITECTURE?
--------------------------------------------------

    Jenkins distributed architecture allows
    multiple machines to work together.

    Instead of running all jobs on one server,
    Jenkins distributes work to multiple nodes.

    Improves:
        • Performance
        • Scalability
        • Flexibility
		. Security 


--------------------------------------------------
MASTER–AGENT ARCHITECTURE
--------------------------------------------------

    Master (Controller):
        • Manages Jenkins
        • UI (Dashboard)
        • Schedules jobs
        • Stores configuration

    Agent (Slave/Node):
        • Executes jobs
        • Runs builds
        • Can be multiple machines


--------------------------------------------------
WHY DO WE NEED DISTRIBUTED SETUP?
--------------------------------------------------
Building on the built-in node can be a security issue. You should set up distributed builds.

    Problem with single server:

        • Heavy load
        • Slow builds
        • Resource limitation
		. Security concerns 

    Solution:

        Distribute jobs across multiple agents

    Benefits:

        • Faster builds
        • Parallel execution
        • Better resource utilization


--------------------------------------------------
HOW IT WORKS (FLOW)
--------------------------------------------------

    Developer pushes code
            ↓
    Jenkins Master receives trigger
            ↓
    Master schedules job
            ↓
    Job sent to Agent
            ↓
    Agent executes build/test/deploy
            ↓
    Result sent back to Master


--------------------------------------------------
AGENT TYPES
--------------------------------------------------

    1) Static Agents
        • Manually created
        • Always available

    2) Dynamic Agents
        • Created on demand
        • Used in cloud (AWS, Kubernetes)


--------------------------------------------------
HOW MASTER COMMUNICATES WITH AGENTS
--------------------------------------------------

    Common methods:

        • SSH
        • JNLP (Java Web Start)
        • Kubernetes plugin

    Master → Agent connection must be secure.


--------------------------------------------------
SETTING UP AGENT (HIGH LEVEL STEPS)
--------------------------------------------------

    Step 1:
        Go to Manage Jenkins → Nodes

    Step 2:
        Add new node

    Step 3:
        Configure:

            • Node name
            • Remote directory
            • Labels
            • Launch method (SSH/JNLP)

    Step 4:
        Connect agent machine


--------------------------------------------------
LABELS (IMPORTANT)
--------------------------------------------------

    Labels are used to assign jobs to specific agents.

Example:

    agent {
        label "docker"
    }

    Meaning:
        Run job only on agent with label "docker"


--------------------------------------------------
REAL-TIME DEVOPS USE CASE
--------------------------------------------------

    Scenario:

        • Java builds require Maven
        • Docker builds require Docker
        • Testing needs separate environment

    Setup:

        Agent 1 → Java + Maven
        Agent 2 → Docker
        Agent 3 → Testing tools

    Jenkins routes jobs accordingly.


--------------------------------------------------
ADVANCED SETUP (CLOUD)
--------------------------------------------------

    Jenkins can create agents dynamically:

        • AWS EC2 plugin
        • Kubernetes plugin

    Flow:

        Job triggered
            ↓
        New agent created
            ↓
        Job executed
            ↓
        Agent terminated

    Benefit:
        Cost optimization


--------------------------------------------------
ADVANTAGES
--------------------------------------------------

    • Parallel builds
    • Faster execution
    • Scalable
    • Supports multiple environments
    • Efficient resource usage


--------------------------------------------------
DISADVANTAGES
--------------------------------------------------

    • Setup complexity
    • Network dependency
    • Agent management needed


--------------------------------------------------
IMPORTANT NOTES
--------------------------------------------------

    • Master should NOT run heavy jobs
    • Always use agents for execution
    • Secure communication (SSH keys)
    • Use labels for control


--------------------------------------------------
SIMPLE SUMMARY
--------------------------------------------------

    Master:
        Controls everything

    Agent:
        Executes jobs

    Distributed Jenkins:
        One master → Multiple agents

    Purpose:
        Faster, scalable CI/CD execution
		
		
